# Meeting Prep Pack

Walking into a board or committee meeting without preparation is a career risk. This skill generates a structured brief that pulls key numbers, talking points, risk items, and decision requests from the workbook so the presenter is fully prepared.

## 1. When to Use

- Before monthly or quarterly board meetings
- Committee meetings (audit, risk, remuneration)
- Investor or stakeholder update meetings
- Any meeting where financial data needs to be presented

## 2. Pack Structure

### Section 1: Meeting Context
- Meeting name, date, attendees (if known)
- Agenda items relevant to financial data
- Prior meeting actions still open

### Section 2: Key Numbers
- Top 5-8 KPIs with current values and trend direction
- Revenue, EBITDA, Cash, Headcount at minimum
- Each with actual, budget, variance, and a one-line explanation

### Section 3: Talking Points
- 3-5 bullet points per agenda item
- Lead with the headline, then supporting data
- Include specific cell references so the presenter can navigate to detail if questioned

### Section 4: Risk Items
- Material variances that need board attention
- Covenant compliance status (if applicable)
- Forward-looking risks from the data (cash runway, margin erosion, etc.)

### Section 5: Decisions Required
- Clear list of items requiring board approval or direction
- Each with context, options, and recommended action

## 3. Tone and Format

- Written for a time-poor executive who will scan in 5 minutes
- Bullet points, not paragraphs
- Numbers formatted consistently (e.g. $45.2K, not $45,231)
- Bold key figures and use colour sparingly (green favourable, red unfavourable)

## 4. Gotchas

- Meeting prep is not the same as the board paper — it is shorter, more tactical, and focused on what the presenter needs to SAY, not what goes in the written pack
- Anticipate questions: for every key number, prepare a one-line answer to "why?"
- If data is missing or incomplete (month not yet closed), say so explicitly rather than presenting partial data as complete
- Prior meeting minutes and actions should be checked — board members will ask about them

## 5. Constraints

- This skill produces TEXT output only — it does not modify workbook data
- Keep the total brief to 1-2 pages maximum
- Do NOT include full financial statements — reference the board paper for detail
- All numbers must be traceable to workbook cells
